{
    "unitNumber": 18,
    "text": {
        "title": "The Future Tense",
        "sections": [
            {
                "title": "Use of the Future Tense",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 1,
                        "content": "The future tense is, of course, used to refer to events which will happen in the future, as in the following examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Venerdì ***andremo*** in piscina.", "On Friday we will go to the swimming pool."],
                                ["Non so quando ***partirò***.", "I don’t know when I will leave."],
                                ["***Verrà*** anche l’anno prossimo, Signora?", "Will you come/be coming again next year(, Madam?)"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 2,
                        "content": "The future is also used to express probability, or a guess:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Anna non risponde: ***sarà*** fuori.", "Anna’s not answering: she must/she’ll be out."],
                                ["***Saranno*** le 5.", "It’s probably/It’ll be about 5 o’clock."],
                                ["La madre di Pietro ***avrà*** 30 anni.", "Pietro’s mother must be around 30."],
                                ["Chi ***sarà***?", "Who can that be?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 3,
                        "content": "The future can also correspond to the English present progressive (‘I’m going to . . .’ etc.):",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Gli ***parlerò*** presto.", "I’m going to talk/I’ll be talking to them soon."],
                                ["***Porterò*** i miei CD.", "I’m going to bring/I’ll be bringing my CDs."],
                                ["Gli ***direte*** la verità?", "Are you going to tell him the truth?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 4,
                        "content": "In general, the future tense is used less in Italian than in English, and it is often possible, when talking about something which we are almost sure will happen, to use the present:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Partono** domani.", "They are leaving tomorrow."],
                                ["**Viene** anche l’anno prossimo.", "He/she is coming again next year."],
                                ["L’anno prossimo sono all’università.", "Next year I’ll be at university"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 5,
                        "content": "However, in certain cases Italian uses the future where English uses the present. Take this English sentence: ‘When/If I earn/am earning good money, I’ll buy a car.’ Here, ‘when’ and ‘if’ actually refer to an action *in the future*; in cases like this, Italian normally uses the future tense:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Se guadagnerò bene, comprerò una macchina.", "If I earn/am earning good money, I’ll buy a car."],
                                ["Quando arriverà, le mostreremo il centro commerciale.", "When she arrives, we’ll show her the shopping mall."]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "The forms of the future indicative",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 6,
                        "content": "The future tense is formed by adding to the stem of the verb the following endings, which are the same for all three conjugations (**-are**, **-ere**, **-ire**):",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["", "-are", "-ere", "-ire"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["(io)", "-erò", "-erò", "-irò"],
                                ["(tu)", "-erai", "-erai", "-irai"],
                                ["(lui/lei)", "-erà", "-erà", "-irà"],
                                ["(noi)", "-eremo", "-eremo", "-iremo"],
                                ["(voi)", "-erete", "-erete", "-irete"],
                                ["(loro)", "-eranno", "-eranno", "-iranno"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Regular verbs ending in **-are**",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Parlare (To speak)", "", ""],
                            "rows": [
                                ["io", "parlerò", "I will speak"],
                                ["tu", "parlerai", "you will speak"],
                                ["lui/lei", "parlerà", "he/she/it will speak"],
                                ["noi", "parleremo", "we will speak"],
                                ["voi", "parlerete", "you will speak"],
                                ["loro", "parleranno", "they will speak"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Regular verbs ending in **-ere**",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Vendere (To sell)", "", ""],
                            "rows": [
                                ["io", "venderò", "I will sell"],
                                ["tu", "venderai", "you will sell"],
                                ["lui/lei", "venderà", "he/she/it will sell"],
                                ["noi", "venderemo", "we will sell"],
                                ["voi", "venderete", "you will sell"],
                                ["loro", "venderanno", "they will sell"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Regular verbs ending in **-ire**",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Partire (To leave)", "", ""],
                            "rows": [
                                ["io", "partirò", "I will leave"],
                                ["tu", "partirai", "you will leave"],
                                ["lui/lei", "partirà", "he/she/it will leave"],
                                ["noi", "partiremo", "we will leave"],
                                ["voi", "partirete", "you will leave"],
                                ["loro", "partiranno", "they will leave"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "table":{
                            "rows": [
                                ["Dopo un mese in Italia, ***parlerai*** meglio italiano.", "After a month in Italy, you’ll speak Italian better"],
                                ["***Prenderò*** il treno delle 8.", "I’ll get the eight o’clock train."],
                                ["***Partiranno*** domani mattina presto.","They will leave early tomorrow morning."],
                                ["Domenica prossima ***finirò*** di lavorare verso le 5.", "Next Sunday I’ll finish work at about five."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 7,
                        "content": "Verbs ending in **-care** and **-gare** add **h** before the endings of the future in order to keep the hard sound of **c** and **g**:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers": ["Cercare",  "Pagare"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["cercherò", "pagherò"],
                                ["cercherai", "pagherai"],
                                ["cercherà", "pagherà"],
                                ["cercheremo", "pagheremo"],
                                ["cercherete", "pagherete"],
                                ["cercheranno", "pagheranno"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows": [
                                ["Quando arriveremo a Roma ***cercheremo*** un albergo economico.", "When we arrive in Rome we’ll look for a cheap hotel."],
                                ["Mio padre ***pagherà*** tutte le spese.", "My father will pay all the expenses."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 8,
                        "content": "Verbs ending in **-ciare** and **-giare** drop **-i** in the future:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers": ["Cominciare", "Mangiare"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["comin***ce***rò", "man***ge***rò"],
                                ["comin***ce***rai", "man***ge***rai"],
                                ["comin***ce***rà", "man***ge***rà"],
                                ["comin***ce***remo", "man***ge***remo"],
                                ["comin***ce***rete", "man***ge***rete"],
                                ["comin***ce***ranno", "man***ge***ranno"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["***Comincerò*** a lavorare venerdì prossimo", "I’ll start work(ing) next Friday"],
                                ["***Mangerai*** in mensa?", "Will you eat/be eating in the canteen?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Future of some irregular verbs",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 9,
                        "content": "Essere and avere are irregular:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers":["Essere", "Avere"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["sarò", "avrò"],
                                ["sarai", "avrai"],
                                ["sarà", "avrà"],
                                ["saremo", "avremo"],
                                ["sarete", "avrete"],
                                ["saranno", "avranno"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Se domenica sarà bello lavoreremo in giardino.", "If the weather is good on Sunday, we’ll work in the garden."],
                                ["Se avrò tempo ti aiuterò.", "If I’ve got time, I’ll help you."]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 10,
                        "content": "**Dare**, **fare** and **stare** follow the same pattern as **essere**:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Dare", "Fare", "Sare"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["darò", "farò", "starò"],
                                ["darai", "farai", "starai"],
                                ["darà", "farà", "starà"],
                                ["daremo", "faremo", "staremo"],
                                ["darete", "farete", "starete"],
                                ["daranno", "faranno", "staranno"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows":[
                                ["Mia sorella ***darà*** una festa per il suo compleanno.", "My sister will give/is giving a party for her birthday."],
                                ["Cosa ***farai*** dopo l’università?", "What will you do/are you doing after university?"],
                                ["Domani ***starai*** meglio.", "You’ll feel better tomorrow"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 11,
                        "content": "**Andare**, **cadere** (to fall), **dovere**, **potere**, **sapere**, **vedere** and **vivere** follow the same pattern as **avere**:",
                        "table":{
                            "headers": ["Andare", "Cadere", "Dovere", "Potere", "Sapere", "Vedere", "Vivere"],
                            "rows":[
                                ["andrò", "cadrò", "dovrò", "potrò", "saprò", "vedrò", "vivrò"],
                                ["andrai", "cadrai", "dovrai", "potrai", "saprai", "vedrai", "vivrai"],
                                ["andrà", "cadrà", "dovrà", "potrà", "saprà", "vedrà", "vivrà"],
                                ["andremo", "cadremo", "dovremo", "potremo", "sapremo", "vedremo", "vivremo"],
                                ["andrete", "cadrete", "dovrete", "potrete", "saprete", "vedrete", "vivrete"],
                                ["andranno", "cadranno", "dovranno", "potranno", "sapranno", "vedranno", "vivranno"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table":{
                            "rows": [
                                ["***Andremo*** alla festa solo se ci inviteranno.", "We’ll only go to the party if they invite us."],
                                ["Il governo è impopolare e ***cadrà*** presto.", "The government is unpopular and will soon fall."],
                                ["Credo che ***dovrò*** partire presto.", "I think I’ll have to leave early."],
                                ["Non so se ***potrò*** venire.", "I don’t know whether I’ll be able to come."],
                                ["Non ***sapremo*** mai la verità.", "We will never know the truth."],
                                ["Quando ***vedrai*** i tuoi amici?", "When will you/are you going to see your friends?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 12,
                        "content": "A third group of irregular verbs, comprising **bere**, **rimanere**, **venire**, **volere**, and **tenere** (to keep/hold), have the following pattern:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["", "Bere", "Rimanere", "Venire", "Volere", "Tenere"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["-rrò", "berrò", "rimarrò", "verrò", "vorrò", "terrò"],
                                ["-rrai", "berrai", "rimarrai", "verrai", "vorrai", "terrai"],
                                ["-rrà", "berrà", "rimarrà", "verrà", "vorrà", "terrà"],
                                ["-rremo", "berremo", "rimarremo", "verremo", "vorremo", "terremo"],
                                ["-rrete", "berrete", "rimarrete", "verrete", "vorrete", "terrete"],
                                ["-rranno", "berranno", "rimarranno", "verranno", "vorranno", "terranno"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Sono sicuro che mio fratello non **berrà** mai quella tisana.", "I’m sure my brother will never drink that herbal tea."],
                                ["Quanto tempo **rimarrete** in Italia, Signori Boi?", "How long will you/are you going to stay in Italy, Mrs and Mr Boi?"],
                                ["Hanno detto che **verranno** a trovarci.", "They said they will come and see us."],
                                ["Non so se **vorrò** andare all’università, dopo il liceo.", "I don’t know whether I will want to go to university after secondary school."],
                                ["Dove **terrai** la bici?", "Where are you going to keep the bike?"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "id": 13,
                        "content": "All verbs ending in **-urre** have the following pattern:",
                        "table": {
                            "headers": ["Tradurre (To translate)", "Italian", "English"],
                            "rows": [
                                ["io", "tradurrò", "I will translate"],
                                ["tu", "tradurrai", "you will translate"],
                                ["lui/lei", "tradurrà", "he/she/it will translate"],
                                ["noi", "tradurremo", "we will translate"],
                                ["voi", "tradurrete", "you will translate"],
                                ["loro", "tradurranno", "they will translate"]
                            ]
                        }
                    },
                    {
                        "content": "Examples:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["Carlo non parla tedesco, ma un interprete **tradurrà** tutto per lui.", "Carlo doesn’t speak German, but an interpreter is going to/will translate everything for him."]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "title": "Negative Form",
                "paragraphs": [
                    {
                        "id": 14,
                        "content": "As usual, the negative is formed by putting **non** before the verb:",
                        "table": {
                            "rows": [
                                ["**Non andrò** alla festa.", "I’m not going to the party."],
                                ["**Non rimarremo** molto.", "We won’t stay long."],
                                ["**Non gli parlerò** mai più!", "I will never speak to him again!"]
                            ]
                        }
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
